abstract: GLACIAL DEPOSITS. -- They are of three principal kinds -- ground moraine, terminal moraine, and erratic boulders. Ground moraine is composed of the pulverized detritus of worn-down strata, spread out, in part by the agency of turbid glacier streams, over great tracts of land. A large part of the surface soil of Great Britain and North America, known geologically as "boulder clay," "till," or "drift," has thus originated.
